{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638751","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638751"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:58:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:58:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17735"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17735","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17735"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10449"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74736"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10449","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10449"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17735"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60220"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"658"},{"type":"tags","id":"1254"},{"type":"tags","id":"1722"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"8330"},{"type":"tags","id":"11129"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24398"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24400"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45798"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74736","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74736"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-year-old child presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-day history of throat pain and drooling. The child is able to talk and communicate effectively. On examination, there is visible exudate in the throat. The child has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. Vital signs are within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bacterial pharyngitis","Epiglottitis","Viral pharyngitis","Laryngitis","Peritonsillar abscess"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of throat pain, drooling, and exudate in a child suggests an infectious cause. \u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial pharyngitis\u003C/strong\u003E, often caused by \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/em\u003E, is characterised by throat pain and exudate. The ability to talk and communicate effectively makes severe conditions like epiglottitis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpiglottitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a serious condition that typically presents with severe throat pain, drooling, and difficulty breathing, often without visible exudate. The child in this scenario is able to talk, which is less consistent with epiglottitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeritonsillar abscess\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents with severe throat pain, difficulty swallowing, and a \u0027hot potato\u0027 voice, often with unilateral swelling, which is not described here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EViral pharyngitis\u003C/strong\u003E can also cause throat pain and exudate, but bacterial pharyngitis is more commonly associated with the presence of exudate and drooling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaryngitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with hoarseness or loss of voice, rather than throat pain and exudate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Drooling and throat pain in a child can indicate a serious condition such as epiglottitis, but the ability to talk and presence of exudate suggest a less severe condition.","Exudate in the throat is commonly associated with bacterial pharyngitis or tonsillitis.","Epiglottitis is characterised by severe throat pain, drooling, and difficulty breathing, often without visible exudate. The child may assume a tripod position to ease breathing."],"references":["Coutinho G, Duerden M, Sessa A, Caretta\u2010Barradas S, Altiner A. Worldwide comparison of treatment guidelines for sore throat. Int J Clin Pract. 2021 May;75(5):e13879. doi: 10.1111/ijcp.13879. Epub 2021 Jan 7. PMCID: PMC7883223.","Harberger S, Goldin J, Graber M. Bacterial Pharyngitis. [Updated 2024 Oct 6]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK559007/","Sykes EA, Wu V, Beyea MM, Simpson MTW, Beyea JA. Pharyngitis: Approach to diagnosis and treatment. Can Fam Physician. 2020 Apr;66(4):251-257. PMID: 32273409; PMCID: PMC7145142."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60220"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17735"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60220","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60220"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-26T16:42:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-02T08:03:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10449"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74736"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadi